00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:25.430
language by Google.

00:10:25.430 --> 00:10:28.860
The full spec of the language
is at design.google.com,

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:32.300
and pretty much, in a
nutshell, in this presentation,

00:10:32.300 --> 00:10:34.170
if you look to the
screenshot on the right,

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:39.080
material design involves using
complementing in bold colors,

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:42.150
a beautiful typography,
supporting elements,

00:10:42.150 --> 00:10:46.970
as well as floating
elements-- floating papers--

00:10:46.970 --> 00:10:50.320
and it brings together all
these elements of the UI

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:53.720
into one user experience
that's meant to,

00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:55.560
at the end of the
day, make the user

00:10:55.560 --> 00:10:58.200
experience for this specific
app, or this specific page,

00:10:58.200 --> 00:10:59.800
really beautiful.

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:02.419
So it combines the different
elements, and interactions

00:11:02.419 --> 00:11:04.710
between the elements, to give
the user a beautiful user

00:11:04.710 --> 00:11:06.596
experience.

00:11:06.596 --> 00:11:08.470
So you're encouraged to
see the entire design

00:11:08.470 --> 00:11:09.553
spec at design.google.com.

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:15.450
We've see material
design before, mostly

00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:17.770
on Android up till now.

00:11:17.770 --> 00:11:19.700
And over here, you can
see in the screenshots,

00:11:19.700 --> 00:11:22.760
the bold colors, the beautiful
typography, in the calculator

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:24.070
app for Android.

00:11:24.070 --> 00:11:26.510
In the last screenshot,
that's a dialer app,

00:11:26.510 --> 00:11:29.200
and you can see the beautiful
call to action floating

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:31.266
button for the hang-up there.

00:11:31.266 --> 00:11:33.140
And so this is what
material design is about.

00:11:33.140 --> 00:11:34.970
It's about making a
really beautiful user

00:11:34.970 --> 00:11:37.320
interface and
interactions for the app,

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:41.010
and giving your user a beautiful
experience as a result.

00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:44.890
So this is great on Android,
and so I asked myself,

00:11:44.890 --> 00:11:47.570
if I were to build a
new user interface,

00:11:47.570 --> 00:11:49.590
be it on Android
or anything else,

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:52.215
why would I use
material design and how?

00:11:52.215 --> 00:11:53.590
And the first
thing to note there

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:56.050
is that material design
is not just for Android.

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:59.080
Even though you primarily
see it on Android today,

00:11:59.080 --> 00:12:01.460
it's not locked into
the platform in any way.

00:12:01.460 --> 00:12:04.260
In fact, Google is
pushing huge efforts

00:12:04.260 --> 00:12:06.234
into making it
available on the web.

00:12:06.234 --> 00:12:08.400
But you can use material
design pretty much anywhere

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:12.490
you need a beautiful
user experience, really.

00:12:12.490 --> 00:12:14.760
So another reason
I would use it is

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:18.690
that Google has whole teams
doing research around user

00:12:18.690 --> 00:12:20.980
experience and user interfaces.

00:12:20.980 --> 00:12:24.020
For me, as a small developer
team or a lone developer,

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:27.990
I would rather leverage
off this research

00:12:27.990 --> 00:12:31.900
that's already been done and
not have to do it myself.

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:34.510
Another reason is the
tooling is also done for me,

00:12:34.510 --> 00:12:37.380
so on Android in the
form of libraries,

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:40.530
and these days on the web in
the form of material design

00:12:40.530 --> 00:12:42.730
libraries as well,
you're not having

00:12:42.730 --> 00:12:46.650
to bold the elements and parts
of the UI manually yourself,

00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:48.900
There's libraries that
give you this already,

00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:52.430
so a lot of the tooling
is done for you.

00:12:52.430 --> 00:12:56.600
And pretty much the main reason
I would use material design

00:12:56.600 --> 00:12:58.280
in a user interface
these days is

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:00.150
to give the user a
beautiful experience.

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:06.070
Even if you're a lone
developer or have a small team,

00:13:06.070 --> 00:13:10.426
you're now able to give users an
amazing experience, leveraging

00:13:10.426 --> 00:13:12.300
not just the tools, but
all the research that

00:13:12.300 --> 00:13:15.866
comes behind material design.

00:13:15.866 --> 00:13:17.740
So what options do we
have when we're looking

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:20.480
at material design for the web?

