There's Polymer,
which we've heard of,

00:13:22.380 --> 00:13:25.380
and Polymer's been having
material design elements

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:28.610
for a while now,
although Polymer includes

00:13:28.610 --> 00:13:32.560
a lot of new web
technology as well,

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:38.880
and Polymer is about more
than just material design.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:43.090
Polymer's also a fairly large
component, and sort of not

00:13:43.090 --> 00:13:46.360
as easy to integrate
into smaller new apps

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:49.300
compared to other libraries
that are out there.

00:13:49.300 --> 00:13:51.020
So the next one--
and a really nice one

00:13:51.020 --> 00:13:55.390
to get into, if you're starting
out-- is Material Design Lite.

00:13:55.390 --> 00:13:59.990
And so this is a library
provided by Google--

00:13:59.990 --> 00:14:01.660
open source as well.

00:14:01.660 --> 00:14:05.120
The library, firstly, depends
on no JavaScript framework

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:08.190
as such, so it's a
really light library

00:14:08.190 --> 00:14:11.180
and doesn't depend on anything.

00:14:11.180 --> 00:14:13.570
It is optimized for
cross-device use, which

00:14:13.570 --> 00:14:15.430
is really important these days.

00:14:15.430 --> 00:14:19.680
With mobile being really
important within Africa itself,

00:14:19.680 --> 00:14:21.480
you definitely want
to use something

00:14:21.480 --> 00:14:24.180
that's optimized for mobile.

00:14:24.180 --> 00:14:26.590
It degrades gracefully
in all the browsers,

00:14:26.590 --> 00:14:28.330
so it doesn't break.

00:14:28.330 --> 00:14:30.944
And it offers an immediately
accessible experience

00:14:30.944 --> 00:14:32.610
starting out with
material design, which

00:14:32.610 --> 00:14:35.010
was quite important for me.

00:14:35.010 --> 00:14:38.460
So what do you get with
Material Design Lite?

00:14:38.460 --> 00:14:40.160
Firstly, everything
you need to know

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:44.160
is at www.getmdl.io-- the
documentation lives there,

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:46.020
the example, the
templates, and everything

00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:49.260
pretty much getting started.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:51.240
And what you get by
using this library

00:14:51.240 --> 00:14:55.920
is new UI controls that
conform to material design.

00:14:55.920 --> 00:14:59.170
So these are check boxes,
buttons, and the usual controls

00:14:59.170 --> 00:15:01.430
you're used to in
HTML already, that

00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:05.210
have been sort of revamped to
conform to the material design

00:15:05.210 --> 00:15:06.910
spec.

00:15:06.910 --> 00:15:10.320
But you also get some
specialized features--

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:15.100
among them are cards, column
layouts, sliders, spinners,

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:16.350
and some beautiful typography.

00:15:19.130 --> 00:15:21.860
But what else do you
get with this library?

00:15:21.860 --> 00:15:24.990
You get some templates, with
GitHub links to the templates,

00:15:24.990 --> 00:15:27.620
so if you're needing to
adjust the templates,

00:15:27.620 --> 00:15:29.250
they can be done easily.

00:15:29.250 --> 00:15:31.890
And let me show you quickly
what some of these templates

00:15:31.890 --> 00:15:33.100
look like.

00:15:33.100 --> 00:15:36.460
So over on the MDL--
www.getmdl.io--

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:38.950
there's some
templates for a blog.

00:15:38.950 --> 00:15:43.340
We have some templates before
dashboards, text heavy web

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:45.964
pages, and standalone articles.

00:15:45.964 --> 00:15:48.130
So you can leverage some
of these templates as well.

00:15:51.420 --> 00:15:53.780
So you also get a theme builder.

00:15:53.780 --> 00:15:56.070
Material design is about
using a primary color

00:15:56.070 --> 00:15:59.720
and a supporting accent
color in your UI,

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:03.230
and they make it really easy
to choose these colors well.

00:16:03.230 --> 00:16:06.680
So if you head over to
www.getmdl.io, one of the links

00:16:06.680 --> 00:16:10.010
is around customizing
your theme.

00:16:10.010 --> 00:16:12.030
And so you'll pick
a primary color,

00:16:12.030 --> 00:16:14.050
you'll pick a
supporting accent color,

00:16:14.050 --> 00:16:17.630
and you can see to the
right of the screenshot,

00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:19.190
as I pick my colors,
this basically

00:16:19.190 --> 00:16:21.760
changes to show me what
my UI might look like.

00:16:25.580 --> 00:16:29.580
And lastly, there's a really
active and vibrant GitHub

00:16:29.580 --> 00:16:33.290
and StackOverflow community
around this project,

00:16:33.290 --> 00:16:34.460
or this library.

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:37.460
So if you get stuck or you
have any issues around this,

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:40.310
be sure to check out
the GitHub issues link.

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:44.900
Be sure to check StackOverflow
for the project as well.

00:16:44.900 --> 00:16:48.000
So let's look at a simple
example for Material Design

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:49.540
Lite.

00:16:49.540 --> 00:16:51.040
I was chatting to
a friend recently

00:16:51.040 --> 00:16:54.840
who was looking to build
a simple web survey,

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:58.260
and I thought, why
don't I throw together

00:16:58.260 --> 00:17:00.790
a simple web survey for him.

00:17:00.790 --> 00:17:02.960
It was regarding a
product at a store,

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:06.430
so I thought, why not just have
a mock survey around avocados

00:17:06.430 --> 00:17:08.480
at a store called MyStore.

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:12.060
And so I began to put
together a simple web survey

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:14.579
for him using Material
Design Lite to see what this

00:17:14.579 --> 00:17:18.150
could come out and look like.

00:17:18.150 --> 00:17:20.310
So there were two
requirements from him on this.

00:17:20.310 --> 00:17:23.000
The first is that it needs
to be mobile friendly, mostly

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.060
because the primary
audience for this

00:17:25.060 --> 00:17:28.139
was going to be mobile
users, and it must offer

00:17:28.139 --> 00:17:29.650
a beautiful user experience.

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:34.960
So there are many survey tools
and web frameworks out there.

00:17:34.960 --> 00:17:36.910
This needs to sort
of set itself apart

00:17:36.910 --> 00:17:38.760
by giving a better
or a more beautiful

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:42.400
user experience as such.

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:45.340
So in doing this, I used
a couple of the components

00:17:45.340 --> 00:17:47.960
from the Material
Design Lite library.

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:52.330
Some of these are cards,
the drawer-- which I only

00:17:52.330 --> 00:17:55.910
wanted on smaller screens--
then I used the slider on one

00:17:55.910 --> 00:17:59.100
of the questions, I used the
radio box, check box, and text

00:17:59.100 --> 00:18:01.100
boxes for other
questions, and then

00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:04.890
I used the button for
the submit of the survey.

00:18:04.890 --> 00:18:09.250
So let's quickly have a look
at what this looks like.

00:18:09.250 --> 00:18:11.910
And basically, my page
came out to look like this.

00:18:11.910 --> 00:18:15.740
You can see that I've
got a question per card.

00:18:15.740 --> 00:18:18.170
I then have a header at the top.

00:18:18.170 --> 00:18:22.140
I have some links on
the header to the right.

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:24.050
I've used the controls
within each card,

00:18:24.050 --> 00:18:28.605
so I've used the slider, I've
used the radio boxes, the check

00:18:28.605 --> 00:18:31.640
boxes, et cetera.

00:18:31.640 --> 00:18:34.270
And then just to show you
how this is sort of geared

00:18:34.270 --> 00:18:38.695
toward any screen size, if I
minimize this window for you,

00:18:38.695 --> 00:18:41.090
you will see how the elements
sort of arrange themselves

00:18:41.090 --> 00:18:41.590
nicely.

00:18:45.410 --> 00:18:49.260
So we can see that, firstly, the
links on the header are gone,

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:53.520
and they folded into a drawer,
which I can access by clicking

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:55.280
on the hamburger icon.

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:58.120
Each of my cards has
folded to, , basically,

00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:00.240
settle one beneath each other.

00:19:00.240 --> 00:19:02.710
And just to quickly show
you what these elements are

00:19:02.710 --> 00:19:06.320
like in material design, if
you click around on the slider,

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:09.690
you can see that it animates
in a really beautiful way.

00:19:09.690 --> 00:19:13.800
If I click on the
radio box, you can

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:17.720
see that there's a beautiful
ripple effect on the radio box.

00:19:17.720 --> 00:19:20.100
The same goes for
the check boxes.

00:19:20.100 --> 00:19:21.610
And you can see
that it's conforming

00:19:21.610 --> 00:19:23.520
to the color of
the theme as well.

00:19:26.330 --> 00:19:29.950
You can see on the text box that
the hint text sort of floats

00:19:29.950 --> 00:19:32.530
beautifully to the
top as I click it,

00:19:32.530 --> 00:19:35.095
and then the button sort of
gives you the material design

00:19:35.095 --> 00:19:36.030
ripple.

00:19:36.030 --> 00:19:39.090
So it's worth noting that all
these work on touch as well

00:19:39.090 --> 00:19:42.910
as normal web clicks as well.

00:19:42.910 --> 00:19:46.437
So this is what it
turned out to be like.

00:19:46.437 --> 00:19:48.020
And I'm going to
walk you through what

00:19:48.020 --> 00:19:50.240
I needed to do to, basically,
get that page running

00:19:50.240 --> 00:19:51.750
in the way that it looks.

00:19:51.750 --> 00:19:54.140
So firstly, every
HTML page, you will

00:19:54.140 --> 00:19:55.900
need to include four things.

00:19:55.900 --> 00:19:59.930
The first one is the CSS file
based on your choice of colors

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:02.510
for the material design UI.

00:20:02.510 --> 00:20:04.606
The second one is
the JavaScript file.

00:20:04.606 --> 00:20:06.480
It is pretty small, as
you know the library's

00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:08.050
built to be light.

00:20:08.050 --> 00:20:10.140
The third one is the
material design icons,

00:20:10.140 --> 00:20:13.460
which are open source icons
for you to make use of,

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:15.710
and the last one is
the viewport metatag,

00:20:15.710 --> 00:20:17.960
which is really important
to enable this to work

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:21.010
across different screen sizes.

00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:23.210
So the first thing I did
after putting those four in

00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:26.850
is getting some sort
of layout together.

00:20:26.850 --> 00:20:29.900
And what I did here
was, of course,

00:20:29.900 --> 00:20:32.020
so I needed to put
a header in there,

00:20:32.020 --> 00:20:34.262
and Material Design
Lite gives you

00:20:34.262 --> 00:20:36.720
choices of a couple of headers,
so you can have a scrolling

00:20:36.720 --> 00:20:38.740
header, a fixed header,
a header that always

00:20:38.740 --> 00:20:40.970
has the nav bar shown, so on.

00:20:40.970 --> 00:20:43.470
So I've picked the
fixed header over here,

00:20:43.470 --> 00:20:46.170
which means if I scroll,
the header stays there.

00:20:46.170 --> 00:20:50.270
And you can have as many
header rows within the header

00:20:50.270 --> 00:20:52.950
as you want as well.

00:20:52.950 --> 00:20:56.180
So the next thing I
did was define a grid.

00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:58.625
And over here, all I
did was-- I have a div,

00:20:58.625 --> 00:21:01.800
and I've given it a
CSS class of mdl-grid.

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:04.620
And material design grids
work sort of in the same way

00:21:04.620 --> 00:21:07.430
that Bootstrap grids work.

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:11.430
You have 12 columns,
and as you shrink

00:21:11.430 --> 00:21:14.920
the size of the screen
in terms of the width,

00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:18.830
the columns decrease
to eight and four.

00:21:18.830 --> 00:21:20.410
And so what I've
got here is I've

00:21:20.410 --> 00:21:23.360
defined my cells being
four columns wide,

00:21:23.360 --> 00:21:27.940
which is why, on a large screen,
I have three cards in a row.

00:21:27.940 --> 00:21:31.860
If I reduce this, it goes
down to two and one card.

00:21:31.860 --> 00:21:35.350
So the next thing I have is,
in every cell, I've got a div,

00:21:35.350 --> 00:21:37.100
and I've turned
the div into a card

00:21:37.100 --> 00:21:40.760
by putting some CSS classes
on here-- mdl-card-- which

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:43.586
we can see in the
third line of the code,

00:21:43.586 --> 00:21:44.960
and that gives me
the card affect

00:21:44.960 --> 00:21:46.960
you see on the
screenshot on the right.

00:21:50.177 --> 00:21:52.510
So in some of the cards I've
used the different elements

00:21:52.510 --> 00:21:54.750
from-- the control
elements from the library,

00:21:54.750 --> 00:21:59.710
and here I'm just inserting
a CSS class called mdl-slider

00:21:59.710 --> 00:22:03.730
on my input element, and you'll
see that this, basically,

00:22:03.730 --> 00:22:06.550
provides me with a beautiful
slider and the animations

00:22:06.550 --> 00:22:09.630
on the slider we saw.

00:22:09.630 --> 00:22:11.260
This is the radio buttons.

00:22:11.260 --> 00:22:13.210
Here again, as well,
the input element

00:22:13.210 --> 00:22:17.220
simply has a class
of mdl-radio_button.

00:22:17.220 --> 00:22:20.520
The label for the radio
has a class of mdl-radio,

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:23.240
and this sort of gets
them to work together

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:25.610
in the material design
way, and gives them

00:22:25.610 --> 00:22:27.040
the ripple effect as well.

00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:28.780
So for the rippling,
you'll see I've got

00:22:28.780 --> 00:22:34.670
the mdl-js-ripple-effect of
CSS class on this element.

00:22:34.670 --> 00:22:37.320
With the checkboxes, it's
pretty much the same story.

00:22:37.320 --> 00:22:42.190
I've just got mdl-checkbox
on my label as a CSS class,

00:22:42.190 --> 00:22:45.855
and for my input box, I've
got mdl-checkbox_input.

00:22:49.830 --> 00:22:54.190
And for my input box, I've
also just assigned some classes

00:22:54.190 --> 00:22:58.340
to the CSS--
mdl-textfield-- and you

00:22:58.340 --> 00:23:02.520
can see that in the hint there,
I've got mdl-textfield_label.

00:23:02.520 --> 00:23:05.730
So pretty much the common
thing you've seen from this

00:23:05.730 --> 00:23:08.410
is that this library
pretty much involves

00:23:08.410 --> 00:23:12.010
you putting CSS classes in
your already built-up elements

00:23:12.010 --> 00:23:14.400
to give them this material
design effect and look,

00:23:14.400 --> 00:23:18.191
and this is how easy and
what the library's all about.

00:23:18.191 --> 00:23:19.690
There's nothing
fancy involved, it's

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:22.510
just a matter of
putting the classes

00:23:22.510 --> 00:23:24.280
within your already
defined elements

00:23:24.280 --> 00:23:26.140
to give you these effects.

00:23:26.140 --> 00:23:27.640
So here I've got
the button-- again,

00:23:27.640 --> 00:23:29.850
a simple button--
and I've given it

00:23:29.850 --> 00:23:35.050
mdl-button and the
mdl-js ripple classes,

00:23:35.050 --> 00:23:38.040
and this turns it into a
rippling material design

00:23:38.040 --> 00:23:40.109
button.

00:23:40.109 --> 00:23:41.900
So at the end of this,
this is what I have.

00:23:41.900 --> 00:23:47.480
On the full screen page, it
looks with three cards per row.

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:50.680
The moment you shrink that
down to the mobile size,

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:55.320
it arranges beautifully
in a single column.

